{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_ham_ver01/data/sn86090528/00295864655/1920072601/0607.xml":{"full_text":"CHICKA8HA DAILY EXPRESS, CH1CKA8HA OKLAHOMA MONDAY, JULY 28, 1920.\nPAGE FOUR\nCMC KASHA DAILY tiXi'KtiSS\nGEO. H. EVANS. Publisher and HusincKS Manner\nJ. EDWIN TOOL. Managing Kditor\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF GRADY COUNTY\nKntorcd at the I'ostofflce at Chlcknuha, Oklahoma, as Bocond class\nmall matter.\nCH1CKASHA, OKLAHOMA MONDAY, JULY 26, 1920.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES A\"\" \"oneou\" reflection, en\nthe character,, atandlng or\nOne yr, delivered by carrler.$8.00 reputation of any person,\nSix months \"..3.00 firm or corporation and any\nThree month. \".1.50 mis-statement which may ap-\nOne month .60 pear In the columns of the\nOne year by mall 4.00 Express will be gladly cor-\nSix months hy mall 2.00 rectcd upon Its being brought\nThree months by mall 1.00 to the attention of the\nSingle copy so management.\nUITB8 ALL TUB LOCAL KilWS IjEE NW8 BY U. P. WIRE DAILY\nHot Cakes a Campaign Issue.\nAs I lie presidential campaign gets 'under way Hie great issues\nliegin In assume more definite form. AVliile Hie League of Nations\npi ises to lie the main hone of contention between Mr- ('ox and\nMr. Harding, it isn't going to lie the whole show hy a long shot. Al\nready another issue of grave pulilie,interest lias arisen and it calls\nfor solemn reflection on the jiart of t tie sovereign citizens of this\nglorious country of ours.\nThanks to the enterprising gentlemen whose business it is 1o\ndig up readable \"copy\" for the newspapers, it has leaked out that\nMrs. Harding is an expert culinary artist and her specialty is \"hot\ncakes.\" J let- hubby, Warren, who in civil life is Hie CJ. O. I', can\ndidate for president, is so fond of 'em that he consumes anywhere\nfrom fourteen 1o eighteen of 'cm at a meal with nothing but butler\non 'em and then tops off his breakfast by taking on a dozen or so\nmore saturated with maple syrup.\nThe significance of nil this as a factor in the presidential cam\npaign cannot fail to impress the thoughtful voter. For instance, if\nMr. Harding should be elected to the \"White House job and some\ndelicate and threalening international issue should arise, say with\nGreat Britain, all that would be necessary to straighten the muss\nout would be for Mrs. Harding to hastily don her apron, send \"War\nren to the corner grocery for a can of syrup, rush down into the\nkitchen and fix up some \"hot stacks.\" invite the ambassador of\nthe aggrieved power to a breakfast, and, presto, the Avar cloud\nwould blow over.\nWith his sure means of keeping 1 ho country at peace assured\nunder the administration of Mr. Harding, it would seem that the\nDemocratic candidate might just as well get off of the track but\ndon't be so hasty. You don't know Jimmy Cox: the Ohio gover\nnor has already 'met the issue and has gone the Republican candi\ndate one better- It develops that Jimmy himself is some cook and\nmaking flap-jacks is his long suit. The correspondents have brok\nen this news to us, assuring us that when Jimmy goes out on a\ncamping trip lie absolutely insists on doing the king for the\nbunch and not only does he produce hot cakes Ihat \"hit the spot\"\nbut he also knows how to do a slab of bacon to a tasty crisp and\ncan do eggs \"up\" or \"over\" with equal facility. So there you are:\non the cuiinary issue. Mr. Harding hasn't a thing on Jimmy Cox.\nI'roceed with your further arguments, gentlemen.\no\nj 'A League of Peace.\nCritics of the covenant brought back from Paris by President\nWilson constantly center their attack upon Article X which, they\ncontend .automatically draws America into every old world scrap\nthat may arise. Properly interpreted, Article X does nothing of\nthe sort' and it is also noteworthy that the critics take pains to\nmaintain silence concerning Article XII and other parts of the\ncovenant the provisions of which render any great war in i lie fu\nture extremely improbable. The true facts concerning the league\nare brought out by the New York World in the course of an edi\ntorial from which we quote Hie following:\n\"It is a falsehood to say that the League, of Nations contem\nplates war. Every line of the covenant makes -for peace. It is a\nfalsehood to say that nations subscribing to it sacrifice their inde\npendence. On tlu conlrarv. they guarantee their independence, it\nviolates the constitution ot the I niteil\nrespect it would be null and void, no\nI. It is a falsehood to say that it com-\nterl'erence in foreign disputes which\nOur liberty of action in all sucli matters is\n'alschood to say that we are outvoted in the\nleague. Counting our dependencies, we have as many votes in inc.\nassembly as (Ireat Hritain, and in the council, which is the con\ntrolling body, our veto is absolute.\nSo far as die I'nilc States is concerned, the League of Nations\nhas nevei iiad a chance for the lies that have been told about it.\nThe covenant has been distorted, but not, read and not understood.\nIts final rejection on the baseless theory that it compels a surren\nder on our part of the iWeals and rights of the republic would be\na shameless confession of our unfitness for any other association\nthan that which now has been forced upon us namely, with Tur\nkey, Russia, and Mexico.\"\nEXPRESS PACKAGETTEt\nMillionaire Melancholia.\nThe millionaire was dour and Rluin\nWo asked how he was hurt,\n\"The multimillionaires,\" he nobbed,\n\"Treat me like so much dirt.\"\nJudge.\nAs wo fel about it at the present\nmoment, witli the mercury doing its\nbent to climb out at tho top of the\ntube, we would have no serious ob\njections to joining a polar exploring\nparty.\nIf Doc Cook wants to lake anoth\ner throw at it, we're ready to accom\npany him. Thank you for a few gum\ndrops.\nIt is hard to believe, 'but as the re\nport lias been confirmed we'll have\nto accept it: the Chicks won a game.\nAgain we gather fresh hope may\nbe the team is about to enter upon\nanother \"winning streak.\nA ccrlain Methodist minister in\nis a falsehood to say t hat: it\nSlates. Jf it did so in any\nmatter how solemnly ratified\nmils us without recourse to\ndo not concern us.\ncomplete. It is a J\n-O-\nThe Business Outlook.\nAccording to the monthly bulletin issued by Federal Reserve\nHank of Kansas City, which is authoritative on such matters, Hie\nprospects for fall and winter business in this section of the country\nare encouraging. The bulletin issued on July 25 summarizes con\nditions as follows:\n\"Many lines of activity at trade and industrial centers are now\nexperiencing something of the mid-summer quiet, usual lor the\nTenth Federal Reserve district whose large area is devoted chiefly\nto agriculture. Intensive effort is being centered on the harvest\ning of grain winch, under excellent growing and ripening condi\ntions in June and July, is showing yields much larger than was\nforecast by previous reports and making 1020 oue of the best crop\nyears of history. Roughly estimated, the 1020 crop of winter and\nspring wheat in this district is expected to be somewhere around\n2t;0.0()0,00l). Oats is estimated at close to 1S.\".0( 10,000 bushels,\nwhile rye is expected to exceed last' year's production of 11.125.000\nbushels and barlev is scheduled to iro a little better than last\nyear's crop of 2S. 000.0(10 bushels. In dollars, at prices prevailing\nat the markets in July, the value of the 1020 crops of these four\ncereals is about sfOl 10.000.000 while an estimated production of\n400.000.(100 bushels of corn would at July prices add something\nJjke .700,000.000 more to the value of grain crops produced this\nyear in the Tenth Federal Reserve district, exclusive of all other\nproducts of the farms, orchards and ranges.\n\"In the face of the slowing down of trade and industry, re\nflected by the reports covering June operations, there is a feeling,\nin this part of the United States at least, that the good crops now\nin sight are bound to make good business this fall. It is pointed\nout that. while the political campaign may disturb business to\nsome extent, and that the public is becoming more and more con\nservative in the making of purchases and investments, the reports\nindicate that conditions are generally good and such as to insure\nhealthy business in the fall and winter,\"\nthin town confessed to us that he had\nfried chicken twice in one week--twico,\nthink of thut. vo uro con\ntemplating getting a cull to preach.\nIncidentally, it might be well for\nyou to lake a census of tho fryers\nin your backyard und see if uny are\nmissing.\nOn tho whole, prosecution Is a less\neffective method of swatting tho prof\niteers thun wearing patched pants.\nSI Simp says he notices that tho\nheat never Mothers him when he can\nfind a cool place.\nOur old friend, Hank Hardtack,\nfrom the forks of the creek, figures\nthat T. 1'. (lore has about as much\nchanco to get by Ibis Ume as a rev\nenue officer has in a moonshine mo\nvie picture.\nWith the primary ot.ry a woek\nahead, it looks like continuous sess\nions for the Sit-and-Argue club till\nthe thing is over.\nIt's truly tough but all tho great\nissues in this glorious country of ours\nhave to be settled right.\nA STOLEN BMILE 'ER TWO\n\nEvery-day Clothes.\n\"One finds it difficult in these\ntimes to dress as one ought.\"\n\"Oh, I don't know. I huve a suit\nof clothes for every day in the week.''\n\"Really?\"\n\"Yes,' this Is it.\" Tit-Bits, London.\ni\nHis Limit.\n\"You refuse to buy me a new cos\ntume! ((sol) Yet you used to say\nyou'd go through fire and water for\nme.\"\n\"lint, my darling! I never said I'd\ngo through the bankruptcy court.\"\nPassing Show, London.\nA Wise Father\nAbsent-minded .professor meeting\nhis sou Hello, George, how's your\nrather? Harvard Lampoon.\nAnd Green in Judgment.\n\"When are u man's salad days?\"\n\"1 guess they are when he is most\nparticular about his dressing. \"Bal\ntimore American.\nNOTICE\nH you want to rent, sell or trade\nyou